Anonymous Mon 13 Mar 2023 15:51:55 No.55032701 Report
Quoted By: >>55032837
>>55032457
Your problem is that you're trying to get the top edge of the curtains/canopy in frame and not respecting that things get smaller as they recede. Here's the vanishing point suggested by the bed, and how the canopy would fit as you've drawn it. And it looks low because it is. It'd be better to make the distant edge in frame and let it run off of the canvas, because that's a more natural FOV.

Also remember that the vanishing point in 1-point is on the horizon and the horizon line cuts through the same altitude everywhere. So if your camera/eye is 5'6" above flat ground, everything that crosses the horizon line does so at 5'6" high, no matter how near or far it is.

So the right way to draw this is to decide the viewer eye height, draw the back wall in respect to that (floor edge and ceiling edge are 8' apart typically, so if you put the horizon line and VP in the center of the back wall, your eye line is at 4', floor 4' below and ceiling 4' above; put the painting accordingly) then put the bed posts in measured by their side and spacing (near to the wall you know how many pixels 8' is) then use the VP to figure the bed and canopy frame, and then you're set.

>>55032837
Shouldn't take months.

Find an old art book that covers perspective, I'm sure there are plenty of PDF scans on the web. I remember years ago everyone was excited about Loomis. Anyway, practice just laying out boxes in perspective. Do like a week of one, then two, then three point layouts and making rectangular prisms in that space.

Then make you some porn by doing that layout with the boxes being the bounding shapes of your characters' bodies (or a few parts if they're sitting, bending, whatever) and then just draw the characters as you normally would inside the boxes, then disable the boxes' layer. It'll be imperfect, but you'll be closer than 90% of FA shitters who wing it.

Anonymous Mon 13 Mar 2023 21:39:04 No.55039563 Report
Quoted By: >>55040415
>>55039003
I find that the trick is to not instantly jump from your comfort zone into deep uncharted territory, but instead push the edges of your comfort zone ever further. If you ditch your style entirely, it's logical the whole story feels alien to you. Because it is. Try to adapt characters you've used before to the new setting. Not wholesale, but their archetypes.

For example: a sorcerous overlord, Victorian mad scientist or stonefaced MIB interrogator might seem different, but when they've strapped the hero to a table for their unknowable experiments you'll see that they only differ in their tools. The flavor text, so to speak.

That said, it's also a good idea to think who you're writing it for, what they'd want. Often the mood you're looking to create is more important than the details.
